'''''Knightmare'''''{{efn|Known as {{nihongo|'''''Majou Densetsu'''''|魔城伝説|''Majō Densetsu''|lit. "Demon Castle Legend" or "Legend of the Devil Castle"|lead=yes}} in Japan.}} is a 1986 [[vertically scrolling shooter]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Konami]] for the [[MSX]] home computer. It was included in compilations for the MSX, [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] and [[Sega Saturn]], followed by a port for [[mobile phone]]s, and digital re-releases for the [[Virtual Console]] and [[Microsoft Windows]]. It is the first entry in the ''Knightmare'' trilogy. The game stars Popolon, a warrior who embarks on a quest to rescue the princess Aphrodite from the evil priest Hudnos. The player must fight waves of enemies while avoiding collision with their projectiles and obstacles along the way, and facing against bosses.

''Knightmare'' was created by the MSX division at Konami under management of Shigeru Fukutake. The character of Popolon was conceived by a staffer who later became the project's lead designer and writer, as the process of making original titles for the platform revolved around the person who came up with the characters. Development proceeded with a team of four or five members, lasting somewhere between four and six months. The music was scored by [[Miki Higashino]], best known for her work in the ''[[Gradius]]'' and ''[[Suikoden]]'' series, and Yoshinori Sasaki. 

''Knightmare'' garnered generally positive reception from critics and retrospective commentarists. It was followed by ''[[The Maze of Galious]]'' and ''[[Shalom: Knightmare III]]'' (1987), while Popolon and Aphrodite would later make appearances outside of the trilogy in other Konami titles. In the years since, fans have experimented with remaking and porting the title unofficially to other platforms.

== Gameplay ==
[[File:MSX Knightmare (Majō Densetsu).png|frame|left|Gameplay screenshot of the [[MSX]] version]]
''Knightmare'' is a vertical-scrolling [[shoot 'em up]] game starring Popolon, a warrior who embarks on a quest to rescue the princess Aphrodite from the evil priest Hudnos. The player controls Popolon through eight increasingly difficult stages across a Greek-esque fantasy setting, populated with an assortment of enemies and obstacles, over a constantly scrolling background that never stops moving until a [[Boss (video games)|boss]] is reached, which must be fought in order to progress further.<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="KMDhtpJP">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/Knightmare1986KonamiJPRC739|title=魔城伝説|date=March 1986|publisher=[[Konami]]|edition=Japanese|type=遊び方}}</ref><ref name="KMDhtpEU">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/Knightmare1986KonamiGBFR/mode/2up|title=Knightmare|date=1986|publisher=[[Konami]]|edition=European|type=How To Play}}</ref><ref name="LOGiNv5i5">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/login-may-1986/LOGiN%20-%20May%201986/page/n223/mode/2up|title=月刊MSXジャン — 魔城伝説|magazine=[[LOGiN Magazine|LOGiN]]|volume=5|issue=5|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=May 1986|pages=222—224|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="POPCOMv4i7">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/popcom-198607/page/n79/mode/2up|title=Monthly Soft Radar: 魔城伝説|magazine={{ill|Popcom (magazine)|lt=Popcom|ja|ポプコム}}|volume=4|issue=7|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|date=July 1986|pages=80—81|language=ja}}</ref> The player must also avoid or take out enemy formations to gain bonus points, and reveal hidden bridges to cross rivers by shooting at it.<ref name="KMDhtpJP"/><ref name="KMDhtpEU"/>

Popolon is equipped with a bow and arrows as the main weapon, which can be upgraded or changed by collecting a flashing weapon crystal. Picking up a new weapon grants its initial state and can be upgraded by picking the same weapon twice in a row. Popolon can also obtain temporary [[power-up]]s via power crystals branded with a "P" icon that initially appears colored black.<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="KMDhtpJP"/><ref name="KMDhtpEU"/><ref name="Comptiqv17">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/comptiq-vol.-17-may-1986/Comptiq%20-%20Vol.%2017%20May%201986/page/n69/mode/2up|title=Crush The Game: 魔城伝説|magazine=[[Comptiq]]|volume=17|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|date=May 1986|pages=70—71|language=ja}}</ref> These can be cycled through other weapons and power-ups by firing at them, ranging from boomerangs, three-way shots, swords, speed increasers, temporary invincibility and a shield to withstand enemy projectiles.<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="KMDhtpJP"/><ref name="KMDhtpEU"/><ref name="Comptiqv17"/> If grabbed in their initial state, these crystals grant extra bonus points instead.<ref name="KMDhtpJP"/><ref name="KMDhtpEU"/>

Scattered on the playfield are question mark blocks containing chess-themed magic jewels that can aid or hinder the player by shooting a block to release the jewel.<ref name="LOGiNv5i5"/><ref name="POPCOMv4i7"/><ref name="Comptiqv17"/> While many of the blocks are visible onscreen, others are hidden and must be unveiled by shooting at the block until the jewel is released.<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="KMDhtpJP"/><ref name="KMDhtpEU"/> The player can also uncover secret exits within certain stages and warp into the next stage.<ref name="LOGiNv5i5"/><ref name="MICv1i32">{{cite magazine|last=Marque|first=Albert|url=https://archive.org/details/MicromaniaPrimerEpocaspanishIssue32/page/n40/mode/1up|title=Código Secreto: MSX – Knightmare|magazine=[[Micromanía]]|volume=1|issue=32|publisher=Hobby Press|date=February 1988|page=41|language=es}}</ref> Getting hit by an enemy or blocked by an obstacle and scrolled offscreen will result in losing a live stock, as well as a penalty of decreasing Popolon's overall firepower to his original state. The player can obtain more lives by earning 100.000 points each time or collecting a yellow magic jewel,<ref name="KMDhtpJP"/><ref name="KMDhtpEU"/> but the [[Game over|game is over]] once all lives are lost.

== Development and release ==
''Knightmare'', known as ''Majou Densetsu'' in Japan, was developed by the [[MSX]] division at [[Konami]] under management of Shigeru Fukutake, who revealed about its creation process in a 1988 interview with Japanese publication ''Micom BASIC Magazine''.<ref name="MBM75">{{cite magazine|last=Yamashita|first=Akira|url=https://archive.org/details/micomBASIC_1988-09/page/n251/mode/2up|title=山下章のパソコン・ゲーム: ホンキでPlayホンネでReview — TARGET 5 コナミMSXゲーム|magazine={{ill|Micom BASIC Magazine|lt=Micom BASIC Magazine|ja|マイコンBASICマガジン}}|issue=75|publisher={{ill|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|lt=The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|ja|電波新聞社}}|date=September 1988|pages=278–282|lang=ja}} ([https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/187958078198/exploring-the-secret-behind-konamis-msx-games Translation] by Arc Hound. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210925132527/https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/187958078198/exploring-the-secret-behind-konamis-msx-games|date=2021-09-25}}).</ref> Fukutate explained that the staffer who came up with the character of Popolon was in charge of design and facilitating development of the project, as the process of making original titles for the MSX revolved around the person who came up with the characters being assigned to do both planning and the story.<ref name="MBM75"/> Fukutate further explained that the planner would then lead a team of four or five members to proceed with development, which would last between four and six months.<ref name="MBM75"/> Fukutate also claimed they made it difficult from the beginning because shoot 'em ups on the MSX were meant to be played at home.<ref name="MBM75"/> ''Micom BASIC'' writer Akira Yamashita speculated that the game's idea was possibly an arrangement of the Konami [[arcade game]] ''[[Finalizer (video game)|Finalizer]]'' (1985).<ref name="MBM75"/> The soundtrack was composed by [[Miki Higashino]] (best known for her work in the ''[[Gradius]]'' and ''[[Suikoden]]'' series) and Yoshinori Sasaki.<ref name="OMF">{{cite web|last=Mitsuda|first=Yasunori|author-link=Yasunori Mitsuda|url=http://mitsuda.cocoebiz.com/friends/higashino.html|title=This Month's Friend... Miki Higashino|work=Our Millennial Fair|date=May 2000|access-date=2022-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080902011227/http://mitsuda.cocoebiz.com/friends/higashino.html|archive-date=2008-09-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="VGMdb">{{cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/6804|title=LEGEND OF GAME MUSIC CONSUMER BOX &#124; SCDC-00497~506|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2022-09-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211128131137/https://vgmdb.net/album/6804|archive-date=2021-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Greening|first=Chris|url=http://www.vgmonline.net/mikihigashino/|title=Miki Higashino Profile|work=Video Game Music Online|date=December 30, 2012|access-date=2022-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201007210834/http://www.vgmonline.net/mikihigashino/|archive-date=2020-10-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="VGMOa">{{cite web|last=Greening|first=Chris|url=http://www.vgmonline.net/mikihigashinointerview|title=Miki Higashino Interview: Retired Fan Favourite Speaks|work=Video Game Music Online|date=July 1, 2013|access-date=2022-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220802072123/http://www.vgmonline.net/mikihigashinointerview|archive-date=2022-08-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Higashino worked as part-time composer and wrote the game's music, but she did not use the MSX hardware.<ref name="VGMOa"/> [[Masaaki Kukino]] (of ''[[Haunted Castle (video game)|Haunted Castle]]'', ''[[Asterix (arcade game)|Asterix]]'', and ''[[Silent Scope (video game)|Silent Scope]]'') revealed that the game's title is a portmanteau of knight and nightmare, giving it a double meaning.<ref name="GameDev">{{cite web|last=Szczepaniak|first=John|url=https://www.gamedeveloper.com/business/konami-s-games-console|title=Konami's games console: KONAMI - everyone is talking about it. But did you know the company once tried to launch its own console, to rival Nintendo and Sega?|work=[[Game Developer (website)|Game Developer]]|publisher=[[Informa]]|date=May 6, 2015|access-date=2022-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220204224813/https://www.gamedeveloper.com/business/konami-s-games-console|archive-date=2022-02-04|url-status=live}}</ref>

''Knightmare'' was first published for the MSX in Japan on March 29, 1986, and later in Europe of that year by Konami.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx.html|title=MSX's Soft (1983～1986)|publisher=[[Konami]]|date=1996|access-date=2022-08-31|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961108212537/http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx.html|archive-date=1996-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MSXMagFRkmj"/> In Argentina, the game was distributed by Microbyte.<ref name="LoadMSX13">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/LoadMSX/Load-MSX_13/page/n30/mode/1up|title=Soft al Dia: Knightmare|magazine=Load MSX|issue=13|publisher=Editorial PROEDI|date=December 1988|page=31|language=es}}</ref>  Konami also released a slightly altered version that could be downloaded from the "LINKS" network (a Japanese equivalent for internet in the 1980s), where the player could submit high scores to an online server.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cesa.or.jp/efforts/keifu/taki/taki02.html|title=伝説の「THE LINKS」― 世界初のネットワークゲームに賭けた夢: 第２回 — MSXによる画像パソコン通信「THE LINKS」奮闘の日々|publisher=[[Computer Entertainment Supplier's Association]]|date=March 26, 2018|access-date=2022-09-02|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220823055413/https://www.cesa.or.jp/efforts/keifu/taki/taki02.html|archive-date=2022-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Copyright infringement|Unlicensed]] versions for the [[SG-1000]] and arcades were also distributed under the names ''Mó Yù Chuánqí'' (魔域伝奇) and ''Pesadelo'' ("Nightmare" in Portuguese) by the Taiwanese company Jumbo and Brazilian manufacturer Fort II respectively.<ref name="OLD!G24"/> Its main theme was featured alongside music tracks from ''[[Penguin Adventure]]'' and ''[[King Kong 2: Yomigaeru Densetsu]]'' in a compilation album titled ''The Konamic Game Freaks'', distributed in Japan by [[Alfa Records]] in 1987.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/3834|title=The Konamic Game Freaks &#124; 28XA-135|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2022-09-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220624041044/https://vgmdb.net/album/3834|archive-date=2022-06-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1988, it was included as part of the ''Konami Game Collection Vol. 1'' compilation for MSX, featuring support with the Konami SCC cartridge for improved audio.<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="OLD!G24"/><ref name="MSXMag62">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/MSX_Magazine_1988-12_ASCII_JP/page/n17/mode/2up|title=New Soft: RETRO-MSX — コナミゲームコレクション (Vol. 1 Vol. 2)|magazine={{ill|MSX Magazine|lt=MSX Magazine|ja|MSXマガジン}}|issue=62|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=December 1988|pages=18–19|lang=ja}}</ref> 

''Knightmare'' is found in the ''[[Konami Antiques MSX Collection]]'' (1997-1998) compilations for [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] and [[Sega Saturn]].<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="OLD!G24"/> On January 8, 2003, Konami ported the game for [[i-mode]] enabled [[mobile phone]]s.<ref name="OLD!G24"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dengekionline.com/data/news/2003/1/8/445a02f72395c880ab27cb7ffb7bb857.html|title=往年のファンは感激！MSXの名作STG『魔城伝説』がiアプリで復活、無料体験版も|work=Dengeki Online|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|date=January 8, 2003|access-date=2022-08-28|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220828194452/https://dengekionline.com/data/news/2003/1/8/445a02f72395c880ab27cb7ffb7bb857.html|archive-date=2022-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/0301/08/n_konami.html|title=MSXの名作シューティングゲーム「魔城伝説」がiモードで復活|work=ITmedia Mobile|publisher={{ill|ITmedia|lt=ITmedia|ja|ITmedia}}|date=January 8, 2003|access-date=2022-08-29|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211109011225/http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/0301/08/n_konami.html|archive-date=2021-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, the full soundtrack was included as part of a compilation album titled ''Legend Of Game Music Consumer Box'', distributed in Japan by [[Scitron]].<ref name="VGMdb"/> The game was re-released two times on the Japanese [[Virtual Console]]; first for the [[Wii]] on December 22, 2009, and later for the [[Wii U]] on March 19, 2014.<ref name="OLD!G24"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/095/G009507/20091222037/|title=Wiiバーチャルコンソールで「グラディウス2」「魔城伝説」が本日発売|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=December 22, 2009|access-date=2022-08-28|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226170510/https://www.4gamer.net/games/095/G009507/20091222037/|archive-date=2009-12-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Koto|first=Tsukui|url=https://www.inside-games.jp/article/2014/03/12/75089.html|title=Wii Uバーチャルコンソール3月19日配信タイ