''Knightmare'' received generally positive reception from critics.<ref name="MSXMagJPkmj"/><ref name="LOGiNv5i6">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/logi-n-june-1986/page/26/mode/1up|title=Software Review: ンフ人ウェア肢蔵認二友息訴誠シレビピュユー — 魔城伝説|magazine=[[LOGiN Magazine|LOGiN]]|volume=5|issue=6|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=June 1986|page=26|language=ja}}</ref> The French ''MSX Magazine'' described it as a "must have" for shoot 'em up fans.<ref name="MSXMagFRkmj">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/MSX_Magazine_No._6_1986-05_Laser_Magazine_FR/page/n7/mode/1up|title=News: Knightmare|magazine=MSX Magazine|issue=6|publisher=Laser Magazine|date=May–June 1986|page=8|language=fr}}</ref> ''MSX Computing'' saw its visuals as very innovative and found the audio to be acceptable, but felt that the game was similar to ''Sky Jaguar''.<ref name="MSXComKMJ"/> ''MSX Computer Magazine'' recommended it for action fans and regarded it as one of Konami's better titles on MSX, highlighting the graphics and sound. They felt that the game's variety kept it interesting, but noted its extreme difficulty.<ref name="MSXComMagKMJ">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/msxcomputermagazine/msx_computer_magazine_09/page/n69/mode/2up|title=Computerspellen - Knightmare|magazine=MSX Computer Magazine|issue=9|publisher=MBI Publications|date=July 1986|pages=66–67|language=nl}}</ref> ''[[Tilt (French magazine)|Tilt]]'' concurred regarding its challenging difficulty, while feeling that the continuous automatic scroll was slow and caused frustration. Regardless, they labelled it as "one of the finest" action games on the platform, commending the audiovisual presentation.<ref name="TILTMSXkmj"/> They also named it as the "Best Action Software" of 1986.<ref name="TILThs2"/> 

An editor for ''MSX Gids'' lauded the game's visuals, audio and overall quality, noting its addictive nature but the difficulty as well.<ref name="MSXGidsKMJ"/> ''Micro V.O''{{'}}s Yves Huitric commended its audiovisual aspect, but noted that the character moved faster than the scrolling scenery.<ref name="MicroVOMSXkmj"/> ''[[Aktueller Software Markt]]''{{'}}s Wolfgang Rui noted the game's challenging difficulty but expressed admiration towards the music, stating that it was "the best thing i've heard so far on MSX".<ref name="ASMMSXkmj"/> Spanish publication ''Input MSX'' praised the graphics for their originality and variety, as well as the audio.<ref name="InputMSXkmj"/> A writer for ''MSX News'' regarded ''Knightmare'' as "an authentic masterpiece".<ref name="MSXNewsKMJ">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/MicroNewsN6/MSX%20News/MSX%20News%20n%C2%B03/page/n13/mode/2up|title=Tests: Knightmare — Le Cauchemar du chevalier|magazine={{ill|MSX News|lt=MSX News|fr|Micro News}}|issue=3|publisher=Sandyx|date=April–May 1987|pages=14–15|lang=fr}}</ref> The five reviewers of ''MSX Extra'' commented that it was a fun fast-paced but difficult game. They noted the varied visuals, background music, and sound effects in a positive light.<ref name="MSXExtraKMJ">{{cite magazine|last1=Van Ginkel|first1=Ronald|last2=Ylla-Kónneke|first2=Sascha|last3=Guerrero|first3=Javier|last4=Kuraoka|first4=Hirofumi|last5=Miragall|first5=Willy|url=https://archive.org/details/MSXExtra/MSX%20Extra%2032-33/page/n52/mode/1up|title=Bit-Bit - Software Juegos: Knightmare|magazine=MSX Extra|issue=32–33|publisher=Manhattan Transfer|date=June 1987|pages=61–62|language=es}}</ref>

=== Retrospective coverage ===
Retrospective commentaries for ''Knightmare'' have been favorable.<ref name="OLD!G24">{{cite magazine|last=Barros|first=Alexei|url=https://archive.org/details/21_20191215/24/page/n45/mode/2up|title=Knightmare — Como um shoot em up disfarçado de jogo de ação se transformou em um pesadelo inesquecíuel para os jogadores de MSX|magazine=OLD!Gamer|issue=24|publisher=Editora Europa|date=December 2014|pages=46–49|lang=pt}}</ref> ''[[Retro Gamer]]''{{'}}s Stuart Hunt highlighted Miki Higashino's music for enhancing the gameplay, but found the game difficult due to the lack of save options.<ref name="RG">{{cite web|last=Hunt|first=Stuart|url=https://www.retrogamer.net/retro_games80/knightmare-majou-densetsu/|title=Knightmare (Majou Densetsu)|work=[[Retro Gamer]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|date=October 29, 2010|access-date=2022-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210506034700/https://www.retrogamer.net/retro_games80/knightmare-majou-densetsu/|archive-date=2021-05-06|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[MeriStation]]''{{'}}s David Pérez García and Francisco Alberto Serrano praised its graphical department, lack of slowdown, soundtrack and controls, deeming it as a "must-play" for shoot 'em up fans.<ref name="MeriStatKMJ">{{cite web|last=Pérez García|first=David|url=https://as.com/meristation/2008/10/04/reportajes/1223100300_037235.html|title=Regreso al Pasado: Knightmare|work=[[MeriStation]]|publisher=[[PRISA]]|date=March 6, 2012|access-date=2022-08-27|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220827223624/https://as.com/meristation/2008/10/04/reportajes/1223100300_037235.html|archive-date=2022-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MeriStatRaP30A30jdMSX">{{cite web|last=Alberto Serrano|first=Francisco|url=https://as.com/meristation/2013/07/06/reportajes/1373094000_119424.html|title=Regreso al Pasado: 30 Años, 30 juegos de MSX|work=[[MeriStation]]|publisher=[[PRISA]]|date=August 3, 2020|access-date=2022-08-27|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211010050616/https://as.com/meristation/2013/07/06/reportajes/1373094000_119424.html|archive-date=2021-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USgamer]]''{{'}}s Jeremy Parish compared and found the game better than ''[[King's Knight]]'' (1986), citing its visual style, controls, and music. Parish also regarded it as a technical showcase for the MSX.<ref name="USg">{{cite web|last=Parish|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-most-essential-msx-games-of-all-time|title=The Most Essential MSX Games of All Time — Key titles from the most successful Japanese game system you've probably never played|work=[[USgamer]]|publisher=[[Gamer Network]]|date=June 9, 2013|access-date=2022-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730010747/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-most-essential-msx-games-of-all-time|archive-date=2022-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Vandal (website)|Vandal]]''{{'}}s Emmanuel Castro called it "an outstanding game for its time", noting its difficulty and catchy main theme.<ref name="VandalKMJ">{{cite web|last=Castro|first=Emmanuel|url=https://vandal.elespanol.com/retro/knightmare|title=Retro: Knightmare — Recordamos el primer juego de una saga en los tiempos en que Konami y MSX eran uña y carne|work=[[Vandal (website)|Vandal]]|publisher=[[El Español]]|date=October 3, 2014|access-date=2022-08-27|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220827222158/https://vandal.elespanol.com/retro/knightmare|archive-date=2022-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref> 

In 2014, ''[[HobbyConsolas]]'' identified ''Knightmare'' as one of the twenty best games for the MSX.<ref name="HC">{{cite web|last=Alonso|first=Álvaro|url=https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/reportajes/20-mejores-juegos-msx-67820|title=Reportaje: Los 20 mejores juegos de MSX|work=[[HobbyConsolas]]|publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]|date=April 9, 2014|access-date=2023-05-03|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413102020/https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/reportajes/20-mejores-juegos-msx-67820|archive-date=2014-04-13|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[IGN Spain]]''{{'}}s Jaume Esteve described it as an unusual vertical-scrolling shooter due to the absence of ships and compared its power-up system with that of ''[[TwinBee]]'', writing that "despite the technical limitations of the computer that were mainly reflected in that limping scroll, ''Knightmare'' deserved much more impact than it finally had, although it is certainly one of the games that are essential when it comes to touching the catalog of the MSX."<ref name="IGNSpainKMJ">{{cite web|last=Esteve|first=Jaume|url=https://es.ign.com/retro/92999/feature/el-hit-de-ayer-knightmare-y-maze-of-galious|title=El hit de ayer: Knightmare y Maze of Galious — Konami conquista el MSX|work=[[IGN Spain]]|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=April 28, 2015|access-date=2022-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422050026/https://es.ign.com/retro/92999/feature/el-hit-de-ayer-knightmare-y-maze-of-galious|archive-date=2017-04-22|url-status=live}}</ref> Kurt Kalata of ''[[Hardcore Gaming 101]]'' commended the music and boss fights, opining that "It's a fun game, let down by some technical limitations."<ref name="KMJhg101">{{cite web|last=Kalata|first=Kurt|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/knightmare-majou-densetsu/|title=Knightmare: Majou Densetsu|publisher=[[Hardcore Gaming 101]]|date=May 22, 2019|access-date=2022-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527004341/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/knightmare-majou-densetsu/|archive-date=2019-05-27|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Legacy ==
''Knightmare'' spawned two follow-ups released on the [[MSX]] and [[Family Computer]], both of which fall under different genres: ''[[The Maze of Galious]]'' and ''[[Shalom: Knightmare III]]'' (1987).<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="OLD!G24"/><ref name="MeriStatKMJ"/><ref name="IGNSpainKMJ"/> In addition to the main games, a [[stand-alone sequel]] titled ''Majou Densetsu II: Poporon Gekitou Hen''{{efn|{{nihongo|魔城伝説II 〜ポポロン激闘編〜|Majō Densetsu II ~Poporon Gekitō Hen~}}}} was scheduled to be published in 1987 by [[Konami]] for the [[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]] and [[X1 (computer)|X1]] home computers.<ref name="IO123">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Io19871/page/n98/mode/1up|title=魔城伝説II 〜ポポロン激闘編〜|magazine={{ill|I/O (magazine)|lt=I/O|ja|I/O (雑誌)}}|issue=123|publisher={{ill|Kohgaku-Sha|lt=Kohgaku-Sha|ja|工学社}}|date=January 1987|page=97|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="MBM56">{{cite magazine|last=Koshiro|first=Yuzo|author-link=Yuzo Koshiro|url=https://archive.org/details/micomBASIC_1987-02/page/n267/mode/2up|title=立ちあがれ！勇者ポポロン — 魔城伝説II|magazine={{ill|Micom BASIC Magazine|lt=Micom BASIC Magazine|ja|マイコンBASICマガジン}}|issue=56|publisher={{ill|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|lt=The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|ja|電波新聞社}}|date=February 1987|pages=244–245|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="POPCOM62">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/popcom-198702/page/130/mode/1up|title=Monthly Soft Radar: 魔城伝説II 〜ポポロン激闘編〜|magazine={{ill|Popcom (magazine)|lt=Popcom|ja|ポプコム}}|volume=5|issue=2|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|date=February 1987|page=130|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="LOGiNv6i3">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/logi-n-march-1987/page/n165/mode/2up|title=魔城伝説II 〜ポポロン激闘編〜|magazine=[[LOGiN Magazine|LOGiN]]|volume=6|issue=3|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=March 1987|pages=196–197|language=ja}}</ref> The game was intended to be a vertical-scrolling shooter similar to the original but with [[Role-playing video game|role-playing]] elements added.<ref name="MBM56"/><ref name="POPCOM62"/><ref name="LOGiNv6i3"/> Despite being advertised and previewed in Japanese magazines,<ref name="IO123"/><ref name="MBM56"/><ref name="POPCOM62"/><ref name="LOGiNv6i3"/> it was never released for unknown reasons. The characters of Popolon and Aphrodite would later make appearances outside of the trilogy in other Konami titles such as ''[[Parodius: The Octopus Saves the Earth|Parodius]]'' (1988),<ref name="MeriStatKMJ"/><ref name="IGNSpainKMJ"/><ref name="MBM68">{{cite magazine|author=YK-2|url=https://archive.org/details/micomBASIC_1988-03/page/n253/mode/2up|title=特選パソコン・ゲーム: キャラがかわいい「グラディウス」のパロディ版 — パロディウス|magazine={{ill|Micom BASIC Magazine|lt=Micom BASIC Magazine|ja|マイコンBASICマガジン}}|issue=69|publisher={{ill|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|lt=The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|ja|電波新聞社}}|date=March 1988|pages=258–259|lang=ja}}</ref> and ''Hai no Majutsushi'' (1989).<ref name="MSXMag65">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/MSX_Magazine_1989-03_ASCII_JP/page/n11/mode/2up|title=New Soft: 牌の魔術師|magazine={{ill|MSX Magazine|lt=MSX Magazine|ja|MSXマガジン}}|issue=65|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=March 1989|pages=12–13|lang=ja}}</ref> Former [[Compile (company)|Compile]] staffer Takayuki Hirono cited ''Knightmare'' as an influence on ''[[Zanac]]'' (1986), particularly its power-up system.<ref name="STGv12">{{cite magazine|last=Tanaka|first=Haruhisa|title=『ザナック』 インタビュー|magazine=Shooting Gameside|volume=12|publisher=Micro Magazine|date=May 2015|pages=60–18|lang=ja|isbn=978-4896375091}} ([https://shmuplations.com/zanac/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331185317/https://shmuplations.com/zanac/|date=2022-03-31}}).</ref> In 2021, Konami announced a contest encouraging indie developers to make games based on some of its classic series, including ''Knightmare''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shigeta|first=Ryuichi|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/konami-indie-games-classic-series-gradius-twinbee-goemon|title=Konami is Inviting Indie Developers to Make New Games Based on Some of Its Classic Series — Famous IP from the past may be revived through indie creators' eyes|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=October 2, 2021|access-date=2022-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211220054434/https://www.ign.com/articles/konami-indie-games-classic-series-gradius-twinbee-goemon|archive-date=2021-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the years since, fans have experimented with remaking and porting ''Knightmare'' unofficially to other platforms. In 1992, a [[MS-DOS]] version was created by the group Friends Software.<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="OLD!G24"/> In 2005, a [[mod (video gaming)|mod]] dubbed ''Knightmare Gold'' was released by the Portuguese fan group Amusement Factory, which allowed support with the [[MSX|MSX2]] hardware for smooth scrolling, an upgraded color palette, among other changes.<ref name="KMJhg101"/><ref name="OLD!G24"/> In 2012, a [[ZX Spectrum]] port developed by Climacus and McNeil was released online as a free download.<ref name="RetrOtaku">{{cite web|author=Elpianistero|url=https://www.retrotaku.com/2012/09/25/knightmare-adapte-sur-zx-spectrum/|title=Knightmare adapté sur ZX Spectrum|work=RetrOtaku|publisher=Association RetrOtaku|date=September 25, 2012|access-date=2023-12-14|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210129054125/https://www.retrotaku.com/2012/09/25/knightmare-adapte-sur-zx-spectrum/|archive-date=2021-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="RG110">{{cite magazine|last=Kelk|first=Jason|title=Homebrew: Knightmare ZX|magazine=[[Retro Gamer]]|issue=110|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|date=December 6, 2012|page=103}}</ref><ref name="RM7">{{cite magazine|last=Tito|first=Sebastian|url=https://archive.org/details/RetroManiac-Magazine-7/page/n137/mode/2up|title=Review: ZX Knightmare — Un gran clásico que no ha perdido fuelle con el paso del tiempo|magazine=RetroManiac Magazine|issue=7|publisher=RetroManiac|date=January 11, 2013|pages=136–137|language=es}}</ref> In 2013, a demo for a [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] remake was released online by Spanish programmer Alberto De Hoyo (of Demon Videogames), with the full version releasing in 2015, followed afterwards by a "Gold Edition" containing new features.<ref name="OLD!G24"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Elpianistero|url=https://www.retrotaku.com/2015/08/18/une-remake-de-knightmare-shootem-up-msx-dispo-en-telechargement-gratuit/|title=Une remake de Knightmare (shoot'em up MSX) dispo en téléchargement gratuit|work=RetrOtaku|publisher=Association RetrOtaku|date=August 18, 2015|access-date=2022-08-30|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220830221418/https://www.retrotaku.com/2015/08/18/une-remake-de-knightmare-shootem-up-msx-dispo-en-telechargement-gratuit/|archive-date=2022-08-30|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=nerlaska|url=https://www.msx.org/news/en/knightmare-remake-gold-available-free|title=Nerlaska's Knightmare Remake Gold Edition available for free|work=MSX Resource Center|publisher=Microcomputer & Related Culture Foundation|date=September 15, 2015|access-date=2022-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916233700/https://www.msx.org/news/en/knightmare-remake-gold-available-free|archive-date=2015-09-16|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, a [[ColecoVision]] port was developed by Opcode Games and published by Team Pixelboy, featuring an "Easy" mode but requires the Super Game Module expansion to run on the hardware, while the [[ROM image]] was released online for free in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Verdin|first=Guillaume|url=https://mag.mo5.com/actu/154343/les-jeux-colecovision-offerts-par-la-team-pixelboy-pour-noel/|title=Les jeux ColecoVision offerts par la Team Pixelboy pour Noël|work={{ill|MO5.com|lt=MO5.com|fr|MO5.com}}|publisher=Association MO5.COM|date=December 26, 2018|access-date=2022-08-30|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117133909/https://mag.mo5.com/actu/154343/les-jeux-colecovision-offerts-par-la-team-pixelboy-pour-noel/|archive-date=2021-01-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="CV.dk">{{cite web|url=https://colecovision.dk/knightmare.htm|title=Knightmare © 1986 by: Konami Industry Co., Ltd.|website=ColecoVision.dk|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=2022-08-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212213737/https://colecovision.dk/knightmare.htm|archive-date=2020-02-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2022, an [[Amiga]] port co-developed by "h0ffman" and Toni Galvez was made available online for free, featuring several enhancements and additions.<ref name="AAddict11">{{cite magazine|last=Walker|first=James|title=Onscreen: Knightmare|magazine=Amiga Addict|issue=11|date=March 21, 2022|pages=36–37}}</ref>

